<DOC><DOCNO> AP900413-0141 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-90 1607EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-BRF--ToiletHistory     04-13 0150</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Toilet History,0155</SECOND><HEAD>Toilet Paper Awarded Scholarship</HEAD><DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A paper on the history of the toilet hasearned a high school student a $4,000 scholarship, according to aUniversity of Evansville spokeswoman.   The scholarship was awarded in a History Day contest at theuniversity.   The paper, titled ``Down the Tubes of History,'' was written byMichael Kula, 17, a junior at Memorial High School in Evansville.   ``I wanted to get something that affects everybody, somethingcommon but not like a television,'' Kula said.   History professor Phil Ensley said the paper was well-researchedand interesting.   ``It got the judges' attention for sure,'' Ensley said.   The paper traced the toilet from ancient Greece to modern times.There were at least two references in the Bible to toilets,according to Kula. The first patent for a flush toilet was issuedin England in 1775 to Alexander Cummings, Kula said.</TEXT></DOC>